               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-266-person1424">
                  JANE 
                  LINDSAY
               <interp inst="t18280529-266-person1424" type="surname" value="LINDSAY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-266-person1424" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-266-person1424" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of John Lindsay; he is at sea; our house is No. 24, <placeName id="t18280529-266-crimeloc1459">Farmer-street, Shadwell</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280529-266-crimeloc1459" type="placeName" value="Farmer-street, Shadwell"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280529-266-crimeloc1459" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280529-266-off1457 t18280529-266-crimeloc1459"></join>. On the 7th of April I went out at five o'clock in the afternoon, and left the prisoner, who was my lodger, in care of the premises; I left my property all secure in the back parlour - I returned after ten o'clock; I knocked at the door, but could get no admittance; I went to Mr. Jones, the publican, who got in backwards, and let me in; I then missed the property stated - it was worth more than 7l.; I have found a pair of trousers and a shirt at the pawnbroker's; the prisoner was taken on the Monday following.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. J. ALLEY. Q. How long had your husband been gone? A. About six weeks; I had no other lodgers; he is a <rs id="t18280529-266-deflabel1460" type="occupation">Greenwich pensioner</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280529-266-defend1422 t18280529-266-deflabel1460"></join> - I knew I could find him at Mr. Smith's, an agent, in St. Maryaxe; I left a gallon and a half of rum and shrub in my room.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-266-person1425">
                  SOPHIA 
                  LARDEN
               <interp inst="t18280529-266-person1425" type="surname" value="LARDEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-266-person1425" type="given" value="SOPHIA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-266-person1425" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner brought me this shirt and pair of trousers the beginning of April; I pawned them for him for 4s., and he gave me 4d.; I had not known him before.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. In whose name did you pawn them? A. My own; I do not know the prosecutrix's servant - I saw her at Hicks's-hall, but did not ask her to point out the prisoner, for I knew him: he gave me a glass of gin.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was in liquor, being left with a decanter three parts full of rum - I do not know what I did.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 56.</p>
